  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Enabling access to education through rehabilitation of schools to highly vulnerable girls and boys in West Mosul.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Since the start of the armed conflict in Mosul in October 2016 the city has suffered from immense destruction of public infrastructure and services and distributions of aid by forward-leaning humanitarian actors has proved challenging in protection terms. 

Many schools have been completely destroyed or damaged and hundreds of thousands of children have been bereft of their right to education and access to safe and quality learning environments. The proposed project will respond to conflict-affected school-age children who are in need of access to education in newly liberated areas of West Mosul. The first component of the project will aim at rehabilitation of 30 schools in West Mosul (Tal Al-Roman, Al-Shuhada&#x2019;a, Al-Mansour, Wadi Hajar, Al-Amel, Al-Resala&#x2019;a, Mosul Al-Jadid and Wadi Al-Ain neighbourhoods) including WASH facilities for targeted 33,000 school-age children (13,200 boys and 19,800 girls). The project will also distribute IEC materials on safety, protection and hygiene promotion with learning messages and pictorial depictions to facilitate learning and provide access to education in time for the start of the academic year in September 2017.

Water networks have also been destroyed in Mosul and to date, only a third of the neighbourhoods in the West of Mosul are receiving water via water trucking. The lack of clean accessible water is one of the ongoing given reasons for displacement of individuals from West Mosul. Thus, the second component (WASH) will aim to provide clean water 6,500 cubic metres of potable water per month for a period of three months to newly-liberated neighbourhoods in West Mosul targeting 23,000 individuals. 

In addition, the final component of this project aims to support forward-leaning partners operating in different sectors with protection mainstreaming to ensure humanitarian response is provided in a safe and dignified manner.</narrative>
  </description>
